Miami Gardens is positioned in the north-central expanse of [Miami-Dade County, Florida](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida), [United States](/United_States). It functions primarily as a [suburb](/Suburb) of the bustling urban center of [Miami](/Miami), located approximately 16 miles (26 km) north of [downtown Miami](/Greater_Downtown_Miami). The city's geographical boundaries are rather extensive, stretching from [I-95](/Interstate_95_in_Florida) and Northeast 2nd Avenue on its eastern flank, extending westward to Northwest 47th and Northwest 57th Avenues. To the north, it abuts the [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida) line, while its southern limit is defined by 151st Street. The city's rather straightforward name, Miami Gardens, derives its origin from [Florida State Road 860](/Florida_State_Road_860), a significant thoroughfare that traverses the area, also commonly known as Miami Gardens Drive. As of the 2020 census, the city boasted a population of 111,640 residents.

Notably, Miami Gardens holds the distinction of being Florida's most populous city with a pronounced [majority African American population](/List_of_U.S._cities_with_large_Black_populations). Furthermore, it is home to the largest percentage of African Americans in any city across Florida, with a figure of 66.97 percent, according to the meticulous data collected by the [U.S. Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau). It stands as a vital, indeed principal, city within the expansive [Miami metropolitan area](/Miami_metropolitan_area) of [South Florida](/South_Florida), which itself ranks as the [nation's ninth-largest](/Metropolitan_statistical_area) and the [world's 65th-largest](/List_of_largest_cities) metropolitan area, encompassing a staggering 6.158 million people as of 2020. Beyond its demographic significance, Miami Gardens is also the proud, or perhaps simply pragmatic, home of [Hard Rock Stadium](/Hard_Rock_Stadium). This formidable 64,767-capacity [multi-purpose stadium](/Multi-purpose_stadium) serves as the primary battleground for both the [Miami Dolphins](/Miami_Dolphins) of the [National Football League](/National_Football_League) and the [Miami Hurricanes](/Miami_Hurricanes_football), the esteemed college football team representing the [University of Miami](/University_of_Miami). A city, it seems, with a rather intense relationship with organized sport.

## History

The narrative of Miami Gardens is, like many such places, etched with the shifting sands of demographic and social change. In the wake of the substantial infrastructure project that was the construction of [I-95](/Interstate_95_in_Florida) in the late 1960s, a notable migration pattern emerged. Many [middle](/Middle_class)- and [upper-income](/Upper_class) [African American](/African_American) and [West Indian American](/West_Indian_American) families embarked on a movement, a quiet [flight](/Black_flight), from established [Miami](/Miami) neighborhoods such as [Liberty City](/Liberty_City_(Miami)). Their destination was the area that would eventually coalesce into Miami Gardens, a region previously fragmented into distinct communities like [Carol City](/Carol_City,_Florida), [Norland](/Norland,_Florida), or [Norwood](/Norwood,_Florida). This demographic shift was largely enabled by the outlawing of race-based [covenants](/Covenant_(law)) through the implementation of the landmark [Fair Housing Act](/Fair_Housing_Act). Concurrently, a different movement occurred, with primarily [lower income](/American_lower_class) Black residents settling into the neighborhoods of Liberty City and [Little Haiti](/Little_Haiti), areas surrounding significant housing projects like [Liberty Square](/Liberty_Square_(Miami)) and [Edison Courts](/Edison_Courts). It is a testament to the enduring, if often uncomfortable, interplay of economic opportunity and racial dynamics in urban development.

Miami Gardens, as a unified municipal entity, formally achieved its [incorporation](/Municipal_corporation) on May 13, 2003. Prior to this, the collection of distinct [neighborhoods](/Neighborhood) that now constitute the city—including [Andover](/Andover,_Florida), [Bunche Park](/Bunche_Park,_Florida), [Carol City](/Carol_City,_Florida), [Lake Lucerne](/Lake_Lucerne,_Florida), [Norland](/Norland,_Florida), [Opa-locka North](/Opa-locka_North,_Florida), and [Scott Lake](/Scott_Lake,_Florida)—existed as [unincorporated areas](/Unincorporated_area) directly administered by [Miami-Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida). This incorporation was, presumably, an attempt to gain more local control over their collective destiny, or perhaps merely to streamline the administrative overhead.

In 2007, then-Mayor [Shirley Gibson](/Shirley_Gibson) made a rather definitive statement, declaring that the city would no longer sanction any new [low-income housing](/Low-income_housing) developments. This policy shift was reportedly driven by the sentiments of many residents who attributed the proliferation of crime and the widespread use of [recreational drugs](/Recreational_drug) throughout the city to these developments. It’s a common enough narrative, attributing societal ills to the most vulnerable. Around that same period, the city's [tax revenues](/Tax_revenue) plummeted, reaching the unenviable position of being the third-lowest in all of Miami-Dade County. Correlation, of course, is not causation, but the timing is certainly… interesting.

By 2012, [Oliver Gilbert](/Oliver_Gilbert), who then held the distinction of being only the city's second mayor, put forth a proposal for the establishment of a [community redevelopment agency](/Community_redevelopment_agency) (CRA). These agencies, for those unfamiliar with the bureaucratic intricacies, are typically formed with the explicit purpose of eradicating what is officially termed "[slum](/Slum) and [blight](/Urban_blight)." Their mandate extends to improving the physical environment of the city, ostensibly to combat the myriad social and economic problems frequently associated with such designated areas. CRAs are financed through increases in property taxes, with these additional funds then strategically deployed, in part, to incentivize private investment in the rehabilitation and revitalization of the community. A noble goal, perhaps, if one believes that throwing money at symptoms can truly address the underlying ailments.

Looking to the future, [Hard Rock Stadium](/Hard_Rock_Stadium) is slated to play a significant role during the [2026 FIFA World Cup](/2026_FIFA_World_Cup), with multiple matches scheduled to be hosted within its venerable confines. Another global spectacle gracing the local landscape.

## Demographics

The story of Miami Gardens, like any population center, is told through its numbers. While the city itself was only formally incorporated in 2003, many of its constituent parts had already made their statistical debut as [census designated places](/Census_designated_places) in the [2000 census](/2000_United_States_census) and preceding enumeration efforts. Beyond the Miami Gardens CDP, which recorded a population of 2,706 in 2000, the remainder of the city’s population was distributed among the neighborhoods of [Andover](/Andover,_Florida), [Bunche Park](/Bunche_Park,_Florida), [Carol City](/Carol_City,_Florida), [Lake Lucerne](/Lake_Lucerne,_Florida), [Norland](/Norland,_Florida), [Opa-locka North](/Opa-locka_North,_Florida), and [Scott Lake](/Scott_Lake,_Florida). The grand total, as meticulously tallied by [The United States Census Bureau](/The_United_States_Census_Bureau) for the [2020 census](/2020_U.S._Census), revealed that the population of Miami Gardens had reached 111,640. A consistent, if slightly fluctuating, presence of humanity.

