As of the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), the city of Miami Gardens was home to a total of 111,640 individuals, distributed among 30,946 households, with 23,158 identifiable as families residing within its boundaries. The demographic landscape, as the numbers starkly reveal, continued its dynamic shifts.

A closer look at the data from 2016 reveals a granular breakdown of the population's age distribution: a tender 5.6% were under the age of 5, suggesting a modest influx of new life. The cohort aged 5 to 9 accounted for 6.7%, while those from 10 to 14 represented 6.5%. The youth and young adult segments were more substantial, with 15.5% falling between 15 and 24 years old, and 14.6% between 25 and 34. The middle-aged groups comprised 12.7% for 35 to 44, 13.1% for 45 to 54, and 12.6% for 55 to 64. Finally, a significant 12.7% of the population had reached the age of 65 or older, a testament to longevity, or perhaps simply a reluctance to leave. The population exhibited a slight gender imbalance, with 46.9% identified as male and 53.1% as female. Families, those fundamental units of society, constituted a robust 72% of households, leaving 28% classified as non-families. The average household size, a metric often revealing of cultural norms and economic pressures, was calculated at 3.52 members, all contained within the city's 20 square miles (52 square kilometers).

Rewinding to the [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_census), the city's population was recorded at 107,167 individuals, spread across 32,000 households, with 23,749 identified as families. A snapshot in time, offering a glimpse into the human condition. In that year, a notable 6.0% of households were observed to be vacant, a quiet indicator of economic flux or perhaps simply the transient nature of existence.

