## Crime rates

According to City Rating, the [crime statistics](/Crime_statistics) for Miami Gardens have shown a discernible downward trend over the past 13 years. The most significant reductions have been observed in categories such as [property crimes](/Property_crimes) and [violent crimes](/Violent_crimes). The crime rate for Miami Gardens in 2018 was optimistically projected to be lower than the figures recorded in 2016. One can only hope such projections manifest in reality.

However, a closer look at the 2016 data reveals a less rosy picture: Miami Gardens' violent crime rate was a stark 63.64% higher than the national violent crime rate, while its property crime rate exceeded the national average by 30.99%. Compared to Florida as a whole in the same year, the city's violent crime rate was 50.99% higher, and its property crime rate was 19.49% higher. It seems "decreased" does not necessarily equate to "safe," merely "less terrible than before." This section, notably, [needs an update](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers) to provide more current figures, a common enough oversight in the fast-moving world of statistics.

In the year 2016, a detailed breakdown of reported criminal incidents within Miami Gardens presents a rather grim accounting: there were 432 documented cases of [aggravated assault](/Aggravated_assault), a concerning 22 reported instances of [arson](/Arson), and 509 cases of [burglary](/Burglary). The city also saw 24 reported cases of [forcible rape](/Forcible_rape), a staggering 2,743 cases encompassing both [larceny](/Larceny) and [theft](/Theft), and 419 reported incidents of [motor vehicle theft](/Motor_vehicle_theft). The most severe crimes included 22 reported cases of [murder](/Murder) and [manslaughter](/Manslaughter), alongside 265 instances of [robbery](/Robbery). These numbers, cold and unyielding, quantify the human cost of a community's struggles.

The projected [2018 crime data](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers), though requiring an update, offered a glimpse of hoped-for improvement: 286 reported cases of [aggravated assault](/Aggravated_assault), 26 instances of [arson](/Arson), and 435 reported cases of [burglary](/Burglary). The number of reported [forcible rapes](/Forcible_rape) was projected at 7, while [larceny](/Larceny) and [theft](/Theft) cases were expected to decrease to 2,139. [Motor vehicle theft](/Motor_vehicle_theft) was projected at 205 cases, [murder](/Murder) and [manslaughter](/Manslaughter) at 18, and [robbery](/Robbery) at 102. These are, of course, merely projections, a statistical whisper of a better future, but the reality often proves more stubborn.

## Sports facilities

[Hard Rock Stadium](/Hard_Rock_Stadium) in Miami Gardens stands as a monumental testament to the enduring human obsession with competitive spectacle. It serves as the primary home field for not one, but two significant athletic institutions: the [Miami Dolphins](/Miami_Dolphins), a storied franchise of the [National Football League](/National_Football_League), and the [Miami Hurricanes](/Miami_Hurricanes_football), the [University of Miami](/University_of_Miami)'s formidable college football team, which boasts an impressive five national championships within the [NCAA Division I](/NCAA_Division_I) collegiate athletic landscape. This image, taken in January 2020, captures the stadium in its full glory.

Beyond the gridiron, the city's sporting heritage also includes the [Calder Race Course](/Calder_Race_Course), which first opened its gates to the thundering hooves of thoroughbreds in 1971. A different kind of spectacle, for a different breed of enthusiast.

Miami Gardens remains the undisputed territory of the [Miami Dolphins](/Miami_Dolphins), who continue to play their home games within [Hard Rock Stadium](/Hard_Rock_Stadium), a facility erected on land that was once part of the [Lake Lucerne](/Lake_Lucerne,_Florida) [CDP](/Census-designated_place). This stadium is not merely a stage for professional football; it also plays host to the annual [Orange Bowl](/Orange_Bowl) [college football](/College_football) game, a cherished tradition in the sport, and, as previously noted, is the home turf for the [University of Miami](/University_of_Miami) [Hurricanes football](/Miami_Hurricanes_football) team. In a more recent development, the [Miami Open](/Miami_Open_(tennis)) tennis tournament, a significant event on the international tennis calendar, has found a new home on the expansive grounds surrounding the stadium. For almost two decades, the [Florida Marlins](/Miami_Marlins) of [Major League Baseball](/Major_League_Baseball) shared Hard Rock Stadium with the Dolphins, a rather awkward cohabitation, until they finally relocated to [Miami](/Miami) proper in 2012 and, in a move of pure pragmatism, rebranded themselves as the [Miami Marlins](/Miami_Marlins).

Since [2022](/2022_Formula_One_World_Championship), Miami Gardens has also been the setting for the [Miami Grand Prix](/Miami_Grand_Prix), with the thrilling, if somewhat artificial, circuit of the [Miami International Autodrome](/Miami_International_Autodrome) playing host to the high-octane drama of [Formula One](/Formula_One). Because what's a city without a roaring engine or two?

## Healthcare

While the city of Miami Gardens does not, in fact, possess a hospital directly within its municipal limits, its residents are not entirely abandoned to the whims of fate when it comes to medical necessities. A network of health care clinics and facilities stands ready to offer a range of medical care and support. Notable among these providers, located in the immediate vicinity, are Jackson North Medical Center, [Concentra](/Concentra) Urgent Care, and Chen Medical Center, all of which extend their services to the population of Miami Gardens.

Supplementing these larger institutions, numerous smaller health care clinics and specialized facilities provide a comprehensive suite of medical services. These include fundamental [general medicine](/General_medicine) consultations, convenient [walk-in/urgent care](/Urgent_care) options for immediate needs, and essential [dental](/Dentistry) services. For women's health, [gynecology](/Gynecology) services are available, while those in need of rehabilitation can access [physical therapy](/Physical_therapy) and [chiropractor](/Chiropractor) services. The diagnostic capabilities extend to various [laboratory tests](/Laboratory_test), [x-rays](/X-rays), and [sonograms](/Medical_ultrasonography). Proactive health measures are also addressed through [osteoporosis](/Osteoporosis) screenings, routine [vaccinations](/Vaccinations), and programs dedicated to health and exercise. It's a patchwork system, perhaps, but one that strives to keep the machinery of the human body, however reluctantly, in working order.

## Government

Miami Gardens is governed by a seven-member [city council](/City_council), a body tasked with the often thankless job of guiding the municipality. The current leadership includes Mayor Rodney Harris, who has held the position since 2020, alongside six council members. Of these, four are elected to represent specific districts, while two are chosen by the city's populace at large. This structure, theoretically, ensures both localized representation and broader city-wide consideration. The mayor holds the power to recommend key administrative appointments – specifically the City Manager, City Attorney, and City Clerk – with the final approval resting, as it should, with the city council. A delicate balance, or a constant tug-of-war, depending on one's perspective.

